08232nam a22011535i 9783110241020DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20112011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979600295  a97831102410207 a10.1515/97831102410202doi  a(DE-B1597)39244  a(OCoLC)753968370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP302b.S24 2011eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a401/.41222  aET 7602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28031:00aSalience :bMultidisciplinary Perspectives on its Function in Discourse /ced. by Christian Chiarcos, Michael Grabski, Berry Claus. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (282 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v22700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Salience in linguistics and beyond -- tPart I. Entity-based salience in discourse -- tDemonstratives and salience: Towards a functional taxonomy -- tParenthetical agent-demoting constructions in Eastern Khanty: Discourse salience vis-à-vis referring expressions -- tJoint information value of syntactic and semantic prominence for subsequent pronominal reference -- tThe Mental Salience Framework: Context-adequate generation of referring expressions -- tPart II. Beyond entities in discourse -- tDiscourse-structural salience from a cross-linguistic perspective: Coordination and its contribution to discourse (structure) -- tRhetorical relations and verb placement in Old High German -- tPart III. Beyond purely linguistic salience -- tVisual salience and the other one -- tSalience in hypertext: Multiple preferred centers in a plurilinear discourse environment -- tEstablishing salience during narrative text comprehension: A simulation view account -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume addresses the role of salience in discourse and provides broad coverage of various perspectives on and functions of discourse salience. The range of multidisciplinary approaches adopted in the volume differ with regard to the underlying theoretical proposals and foci of research. The topics range from (i) entity-based salience to (ii) discourse-structural salience of utterances to (iii) extra-linguistic factors of salience in discourse. Accordingly, the volume is organized into three sections. Part I focuses on discourse referents and the choice of referring expressions. The contributions cover issues such as salience and demonstrativity in Russian, discourse salience and grammatical voice in the West Siberian language Eastern Khanty, the joined information of syntactic and semantic prominence, and a computational framework of salience metrics. The contributions to Part II are concerned with linguistic structures at or above the clause level. The salience of discourse segments is addressed with respect to the translation of discourse relations and position of verb arguments in Old High German. Part III extends the scope beyond purely linguistic phenomena and deals with the role of extra-linguistic salience in discourse processing. Visual salience in a situated-dialog context, salience marking by hypertextual links, and extra-linguistic salience derived from a mental representation of the described situation are all discussed here. The notion of salience is of relevance to discourse studies in theoretical linguistics, computational linguistics, as well as psycholinguistics.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aComputational linguistics. 0aDiscourse analysisxSocial aspects. 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aIdeology. 0aPsycholinguistics. 4aComputerlinguistik. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aPsycholinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Ling